	('43ab573c-ea3b-4aed-8499-7b1e2e0e7750', 'b0396051-34a1-475b-addc-771e580a5224', '46870047', 'Sales Training Manual.docx', 'docx', '











Libby Story                                  

Sales Training Manual

STYLE AUTHENTIC





100 – THE BASICS OF SELLING

Selling is based around 4 points:

Be real.

Be the expert.

Be directive.

Be thankful.

1.  Be real:

You want the customer to like you.  If you are honest and sincere with a customer it will take you a long way with them. 

-Tips on being real:

Get to know your customer.

Always listen and be in tune to how they react towards your suggestions.



2.  Be the expert:

You want customers to know that you are knowledgeable and trust your opinion. 

-Tips on being the expert:

Be suggestive and show your awareness of trends.  

Offer your opinion but always be aware of their reaction. 

Know where merchandise is in the store and be aware of the brands that we offer.  



3.  Be directive:

You want customer to follow your advice.

-Tips on being directive:

If possible, see the merchandise you picked out on them in the dressing room.  This will allow you to persuade the sale and give an HONEST opinion. 

Always have a solid opinion, especially with a indecisive customer.

If we don’t have exactly what they want, lead them to something that you know we do have that might work.

Always offer to look at our other locations.



4.  Be thankful:

You want your customer to feel and important and return to our store. 

-Tips on being thankful:

Use the customer’s name when referring to them during the whole shopping process. 

Thank them for coming in during check out and again as they walk out of the store.  



Give them our business card and print your name on it for them to reference in the future. 



101 – GREETING AND BUILDING RAPPORT

 “You never get a second chance to make a first impression.”  This statement is true, especially in retail.

Enticing customers to come in the door is hard enough, so what if they are turned off by how they are greeted or worse yet, by being ignored?  It only takes a few seconds to make an impression, so don’t let it be a bad one.  

Every day we have customers entering the store, and studies show that customers form an impression (good or bad) of the store in as little as 20 seconds.  Therefore, in Libby Story stores, we focus on the “Stop and Drop in 15” Rule.  Think of it like your childhood fire drill, “Stop, Drop, and Roll,” but its “Stop and Drop in 15!”

This simple rule defines how you should act in those first few crucial seconds. Let’s look:

Take action within 15 feet or 15 seconds.  This is whenever you see a customer enter the store, or your section, then complete steps one and two within 15 seconds.  The same goes whenever a customer comes within 15 feet of you while browsing. 

Step One: Break the ice and let the customer know that you know they are in the store.  The best way to do this is by STOPPING what you are doing, making eye contact, and giving a big smile.  These simple acts will go a long way to making the customer feel at ease and help them be open to your approach.  



Step Two: Now that you have proven your attentiveness and broken the ice with eye contact, DROP whatever you are working on and approach the customer by taking a few steps in their direction and giving them a friendly “Hello!” Make sure to open your posture by having your body erect and moving your hands away from your body.  



By enacting the “Stop and Drop in 15” Rule, you will be well down the road to creating the positive first impression that is so important to getting your customer in the buying mood. 



Greetings and Conversation Starters

“Tell me what you are shopping for?”

“What brings you in today?”

“Are you looking for anything particular that I can help you with?”

 “… well my name is ___, let me know if I can help you with anything.”

“I like your ____, where did you get them?”

“Are y’all having a girl’s day?”

If a man is with them (talk to him, he is usually the one paying) “Do these ladies have you out shopping today?”

“Let me know if I can grab other sizes for you.”

“I love that ____ you chose. It looked so great on you.” – (only say this if the item really did look great on them)

“Do you need help find a shoe in your size?”



Let’s Apply It: Make a list of five original customer greetings and turn in to your manager. It’s always a good idea to have a few greetings in the back of your mind to keep your greetings original.







 



102 – HOW TO QUALIFY YOUR CUSTOMER’S NEEDS

A few common retail mistakes to avoid:



Failing to find out the customer’s requirements of what they need or want. 

Focusing on your own agenda instead of the customer’s.

Not giving customers the majority of air time – let them do the talking.

Confusing “telling” with “selling” – listen to what the customer is saying.

Not being knowledgeable about the product you are selling. You should be able to inform the customer why they need the item. 

Not knowing the prevailing promotions, specials, and regular prices.



How to avoid these and identify your customer’s needs:



Step One: Find out why they are shopping.  If they are shopping to find a specific outfit for an event or are just browsing, customers will enjoy the idea that you care what they are looking for. 



Step Two: Start suggestively selling them items based on your conversation thus far.  Make real conversation with the customer as you suggest items.  Every customer is use to the normal salesperson/customer scenario, so surprise them with a personable, genuine interest in what they need.



Step Three: Continue talking and working with the customer until you have two or three options for them to try. Focus on the clues that the customer has given you through conversation to help you find what they need. 



Let’s Apply It: You will perform two mock sales scenarios with your manager to practice suggestive selling and adapting to customer’s preferences.  





103 – MOTIVATING YOUR CUSTOMERS TO BUY



Customers are motivated to shop by their desire or need for an item.  Different words and word phrases can help to motivate a customer to buy something that they were on the edge about.  

You – One of the first words that should be used. Why? Because it’s all about the customer! This simple word makes the conversation with the customer seem more personal.

Guarantee – Providing a guarantee makes one feel safe with her buying choices.

Discover – People are curious and want to find new things. This word can position your products as something new and exciting, just waiting to be found.

Love – As in “You are going to LOVE this product!” Customers want to love their purchases and you can help them do it. Even better…. they want their friends and family to love them when they give a gift that was purchased in Libby Story. 

Save – Everyone wants to save something, whether it’s time, money, or trouble.

New – Having the newest item out there helps people feel like they’re above and beyond the crowd. Think: keeping up with the Jonses.

One-of-a-kind – This phase grabs the attention of customers that want a unique and individual look.  If they know that a piece is one-of-a-kind they will feel like they are being trendsetters.  A good example to use this phase on is our Lenna Agnes line. 

Let’s Apply It: Choose seven new items within the store and “sell” them to your manager by using a phrase containing each of the seven key words above. 





104 – MAXIMIZING THE DRESSING ROOM OPPORTUNITY

Once a customer is in the fitting room, it’s a perfect opportunity to introduce more merchandise.  

Step One: Once your customer is in the dressing room, stick around and be available for anything they may need. Some customers will come out of the dressing room to view their items in the bigger mirror – nine time out of ten they want your opinion. If the customer does not come out of their room, give them a few minutes and check on them being sure to call them by name. 



Step Two: If you don’t feel confident that they are completely satisfied with what they have tried on thus far, find a few more items and nonchalantly place them on their door and let them know you have found a few more options for them. 

NOTE: Giving a customer too many options can confuse them and lead to no sale at all. It’s always helpful to offer to clear out any unwanted items for the customer as they are trying on to avoid clutter and confusion. 



Step Three: Once you feel confident that they have found what they are looking for it’s a great idea to suggest items that complement what they have found or complete their look. 

NOTE: If the customer is just browsing and not looking for anything specific, pay attention to what they are adding so that you can suggest matching items once they are trying on.   

When giving your opinion of the outfit and how it looks be HONEST and suggestive! You don’t want them to buy it and then get home and their best friend tells them that it looks terrible on them.  



The key to maximizing the dressing room opportunity is to know when to suggest and when not to suggest.  If the customer is not receptive of your advice then the best thing to do is to let them be until they get done.  The biggest sales will go to the most aggressive customer motivators, not the most aggressive customer pushers.



Let’s Apply It: Today, bring all of your customers two add-ons while they are in the dressing room. 





105 – TECHNICQUES FOR CLOSING THE SALE

When the customer is finished trying on and is coming out of the dressing room the best thing to ask is if anything worked out for them.  When taking unwanted items from customers that are leaving the dressing room empty handed, always offer to help them find something else.

If the customer is on the fence about buying an item, remember you are the expert! Have a solid opinion about what you think they should choose. A customer is much more likely to listen to someone who is confident and honest with their opinions. 

If you remember certain outfits that they tried on, you could also ask if they had decided to get the ___ outfit.  This gives you the opportunity to once again give them your opinion.  

Don’t rush the customer to the register right after they get out of the dressing room.  Ask them if you can take the clothes that they already tried on and want and put them behind the register until they are ready.  Don’t linger behind the register because it will make the customer feel rushed. 

Allow them time to browse and possibly even try on more clothes.  If you feel the customer is open to it, suggest jewelry or other complimentary items to what they are buying. 

Let’s Apply It: Focus on suggesting add-on items at the checkout to three of your customers today. 





106 – FOLLOWING UP AND BUILDING REFERRALS

Before the customer leaves, it is a good idea to give them a business card with your name written on it. This will enable them to ask for you the next time they come in or even suggest you to their friends. After having a personal shopping experience with a customer, fill out a personal customer sheet so that next time they come in you can remember their size, style, and personal details.  This will amaze them and make them feel very important to the store.  

It is also important to follow-up with them after they come in.  

Ways to Follow-up:



If you felt a real connection with them you could call them in a few days to see how their outfit worked out.  

Another way to follow-up is to send a thank you note.  By doing this, the customer knows that you took the time to sit down and hand write them a note of appreciation.  

Within the thank you note try to remember things from the conversation that you had with them.  This will impress the customer and show them that your conversation with genuine. 

If you haven’t seen a customer in a while, try to touch base with them and get them in the store. 

Be sure to contact your customers when we get new items in that you think they would like. 

Let’s Apply It: For your first three customer interactions be sure to write a personal thank you note and read over it with your manager.





107 – OVERCOMING OBSTABLES WITH DIFFICULT CUSTOMERS

The customer is ALWAYS right! 

We will not always have the specific item that a customer is looking for; however it is your job to be suggestive and think on your toes in order to persuade the customer in a new direction and save the sale. 

Ways to ensure that we take advantage of every customer that comes into our store with a specific need:

Always offer to check our other locations for the item that they are looking for.  

If that fails, recommend something else that may be similar.  Never come back empty handed.  If something is sold out, present something you think they would like. 

If we don’t have anything remotely like the item, try to figure out why they need the item and find a new solution.

Example: A girl comes in looking for a black and white striped top. If you can’t find one, ask the customer what they are planning to wear the black and white striped top with.  Once you know what the bottoms are, you can suggest another top that would match as well.  

Make sure you take clues from what they are telling you based on what you are suggesting and be able to change your suggestions based on the response.

A lot of customers are difficult when they don’t know what they want.  The best way to handle that situation is to be knowledgeable of the merchandise that is available for them. 

Realize that customers are defensive.  When a customer is unsure about something that you bring them make a personal remark or compliment that will put the customer at ease and persuade the customer to try it on. 

Let’s Apply It: Complete a mock scenario with your manager who will portray a “difficult customer”.





108 – RETAINING CUSTOMERS WITH A COMPLETE CUSTOMER EXPERIENCE

EVERY customer needs to have a good Libby Story experience.   Customer loyalty can be worth up to 10 times as much as a single person.  

You should always drop what you are doing to help the customers.  Every single customer counts.

Customers that have negative feedback from our store are far more likely to spread the word than one that has a positive experience.  To avoid this, speak to every customer and offer to help in a friendly manor regardless to how they look or are dressed.  If you offer and a customer doesn’t need help, back off but still be available if they need help.

In retail, business is based on the customers.  If there aren’t customers then there is no business and no one makes money.  This is why it is very important to value and work hard to have good customer relationships. 

The complete customer experience is based on all of the aspects of selling that we have covered.  

Review the steps:

Greet and start conversation 

Start them a dressing room

Suggest add-ons

Follow up in the dressing room

Check out and thank by name

All of these steps are important.  Try your hardest to stay with the customer the entire time, from the beginning to the check out.  





























