	('ed62027e-fc04-457e-a790-28a78b64d378', 'b0396051-34a1-475b-addc-771e580a5224', '46870047', 'Sales Training - How to Add-On to Any Sale.docx', 'docx', 'Sales Training: How To Add-On To Any Sale

We all know what an add-on sale is but do you know how to make it happen?   Once the customer has selected the main product, you have three options to get additional product out the door:

Make them see something else that makes the first purchase better.

Scare them they may need something else.

Fold your tent.

Obviously, you will mostly focus on the first but all three are possible.  

The first is a great one for clothing/accessories where there are substantial ways you can make the outfit perfect. Use the cake analogy.

“Have you ever seen someone make a chocolate cake?” (wait for answer.) “Its pretty good all on its own. What I’m going to show you is the frosting on the cake.”

Simple, sets the expectation, feels easy.

The second is great if you sell to a customer getting ready for a big trip or replenishing their wardrobe.  

“Have you ever gotten home, ready to get dressed and found you didn’t have everything you needed so you had to go back to the store?” (wait for answer.) “We’ve got everything you need right over here to save you a trip.”

The third is what you hear in stores day-in and day-out. It’s called folding your tent.  It is the most heard response from a clerk…

“Anything else?”

What did you see in that interaction?  Nothing.

Know what you’ll get in additional sales with that line?  Nothing.

You have not created a picture either good or bad.

After all the work it took to get the customer in and for them to buy, you buckled when you needed to stand tall.

Think about being in a restaurant…You’ve just finished a great meal. The server comes over and says, “Anything else?”

Quick, what did you see?  Nothing.

What if the server said, “Do you want some pie or cookies or ice cream with that?” What did you see?  Nothing.

But what if the server said, “We have a fresh-made apple pie just out of the oven. I could drizzle a little warm caramel on it and top it off with a scoop of vanilla bean ice cream.”

What did you see? I bet you saw the pie. Don’t care if you opted to order it. You saw it. That takes careful planning.

So, how can you paint a picture for your customers?  “We just received a new shipment of Lenna Agnes pieces.  I could pair a unique necklace with this outfit to make your friends jealous and ensure you have a one-of-a-kind look.”

Carefully designing your sales questions/suggestions to paint pictures raises average check.



