	('5bd04f2c-aae1-421e-8316-bdf091ffe3bb', 'b0396051-34a1-475b-addc-771e580a5224', '46870047', 'Body Types.pdf', 'pdf', 'Female Body Types & How to Dress Them

Body type: Straight

This is the most common body type. Over 45% of American women have a Straight body shape (sometimes called rectangle or ruler). This means that the hips and bust are balanced and the waist is not very defined. Straight body types probably have a bottom that is more flat than round. They tend to gain weight in the torso first and then in the upper thighs and arms. Their lower legs are always shapely and one of the best assets.

How to Dress a Straight Body Shape

The key to dressing a Straight body type is to proportionally dress the top and bottom of the body while enhancing the waist. They can wear form fitting clothing (such as a tube-type dress) and create a waist by adding a wide, dark belt. However, to create a more curvaceous effect, add volume (or the illusion of volume) proportionally to the upper and lower body by mixing and matching separates.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - Pair color of similar or identical brightness on the upper and lower body, while adding darker color around your waist.
• Pair a light colored dress with a wide dark belt.
• Pair a shirt that is lighted colored around the bust/shoulders and dark below the bust with light colored pants or a skirt.

Body type is: Pear

A Pear Body type (sometimes called triangle), is when the hips are larger than the bust and there is a nicely defined waist. Pears have an elegant neck and proportionately slim arms and shoulders. They first gain weight in the bottom and legs followed by the tummy and upper body. The waist is the best asset so don''t be afraid to show it off.

How to Dress a Pear Body Shape

The key to dressing a pear body type is to enhance and add volume (or the illusion of volume) to the upper body while emphasizing the waist and de-emphasizing the lower body to create a balanced, hourglass appearance. Strapless dresses and tops look good on a Pear Body, but you can create a more curvaceous effect and add volume to the upper half by mixing and matching separates.

Tip: Create Balance with Color – Pair light colors on the upper body with dark colors on the lower body.
• Suggest dark wash jeans and stay away from whiskering (faded vertical lines) at the hips.

Body type: Spoon

A Spoon Body type (sometimes called figure 8), is when hips are larger than the bust and there is a defined waist. The hips have a "shelf" appearance, and spoon body types are prone to gaining weight in the tummy and have a tendency towards love-handles. Spoon body types may gain weight in the upper thighs and upper arms, but the lower legs and arms are shapely and the best assets.

How to Dress a Spoon Body Shape

The key to dressing a Spoon body type is to draw attention to the upper body while deemphasizing the tummy and hips to create a more balanced appearance and create the illusion of an hourglass figure. Strapless dresses and tops look great, and since the legs are one of the best assets, feel free to play with skirt lengths and show them off.

Tip: Create balance with color – Look for clothing that is lighter around the bust and shoulders.
• The problem area is most likely the tummy. Shirts and dresses that are darker in mid-section and lighter on top will create the most flattering effect.

Body type: Hourglass

The Hourglass body type is the one that most women strive for. The bust and hips are well balanced and there is a beautifully defined waist. Hourglass shapes have gently rounded shoulders that align nicely with the hips. The waist is obvious and gracefully curves out to the hips. They most likely have a rounded bottom and beautiful side as well as front profile. The upper body is proportionate in length to the legs which are shapely. From top to bottom, the Hourglass is a picture of harmony and balance.

How to Dress an Hourglass Body Shape

The key to dressing an Hourglass body type is to proportionally dress the top and bottom of the body while accentuating the waist. Wide belts over shirts and dresses are a great way to show off the waist. Create an even more curvaceous effect by proportionally adding a bit of volume to the upper and lower body, but always try to maintain balance since it is the best asset. Feel free to play with skirt lengths to show off great legs.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - Pair colors of similar or identical brightness on the upper and lower body, while adding darker color around the waist to accentuate curves.
• Pair a light colored dress with a wide dark belt.
• Pair a shirt that is lighted colored around the bust/shoulders and dark below the bust, and put it with light colored pants or a skirt.

Body type: Top Hourglass

Top Hourglass Body Types have a beautifully defined waist and bust that is larger than the hips. They have gently rounded shoulders that align nicely with the hips. The waist is obvious and gracefully curves out to the hips. They most likely have a rounded bottom and beautiful side as well as front profile. Their upper body is proportionate in length to their legs which are shapely.

How to Dress a Top Hourglass Body Shape

The key to dressing a Top Hourglass body type is to balance the lower body with the ample bust while accentuating the enviable waist. This is achieved by selecting clothing cuts that will fill out the lower half. Feel free to play with skirt lengths and show off shapely legs.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - Look for dresses and separates that are dark around the bust and monochromatic below the bust to create the illusion of a balanced figure.
• Pair a light or bright colored strapless dress with a dark band around the bust.
• Pair a shirt that is dark colored around the bust/shoulders and light in color below the bust with light colored pants or a skirt.

Body type: Inverted Triangle

Inverted Triangle body types have a proportionally larger upper body with broad shoulders, and ample bust and a wide back. The hips are slim and the bottom may be on the flat side. The waist is subtle and Inverted Triangles have a tendency to gain weight in the belly and upper body. Beautiful, shapely legs are the best asset.

How to Dress an Inverted Triangle Body Shape

The key to dressing an Inverted Triangle body type is to balance the broader shoulders, chest and back with the narrower lower body to create more of an hourglass effect. This is achieved by choosing clothes that add curves to the hips and bottom while creating a more defined waist. Feel free to show off amazing legs so play with skirt lengths, but don''t go too short otherwise this will further a topheavy look.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - Look for dresses and separates that are dark above the waist and light or bright below to create the illusion of a balanced figure.
• Pick a dress has a dark colored bodice and light skirt.
• Pair a shirt that is dark colored around the bust/shoulders and brighter in color below the bust with light colored pants or a skirt.

Body type: Oval

Oval body types have a large bust, narrow hips, and a full midsection. They have a tendency to gain weight in the stomach, back and upper body. The waist is undefined and the widest part of their frame. They also have a full, shorter neck and full face. The buttocks are somewhat flat and the legs are slender. Shapely legs are their best asset.

How to Dress an Oval Body Shape

The key to dressing an Oval body type is to de-emphasize the midsection and create a more defined waist. This is achieved by choosing clothing that adds curves and fullness to the lower body and tops that taper to a waist. Stay away from tight clothing (such as a tube-type dress). Feel free to show off amazing legs so play with skirt lengths, but don''t go too short otherwise this will further a top-heavy look.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - A monochromatic look usually works best. Add splashed of color with camisoles, earrings, necklaces and great shoes.
• Wear a dark colored dress with a wide dark belt.
• Wear a dark pant or skirt suit with a bright colored cami and shoes.

Body type: Diamond

Diamond body types have hips that are broader than the bust and shoulders and a full midsection. They have a tendency to gain weight in their stomach, back, hips and buttocks. The waist is undefined and the widest part of the frame. They carry some weight in the upper legs, but the lower legs are shapely and one of their most attractive features. They also have proportionately slender, shapely arms.

How to Dress a Diamond Body Shape

The key to dressing a Diamond body type is to balance the shoulders and bust with the hips while creating a waist. This is achieved by choosing clothing that adds curves and fullness to the upper body with appropriate clothing cuts while choosing pants and skirts that will lean and lengthen the lower body. They have amazing lower legs and beautiful arms, so feel free to show them off. Stay away from tight clothing (such as a tube-type dress). To create the most curvaceous effect, mix and match separates and play up their face.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - A monochromatic look usually works best. Add splashed of color with wraps, earrings, and necklaces.
• Wear a dark colored dress with a wide dark belt.
• Wear a dark pant or skirt suit with a bright colored cami/scarf.', 'Female Body Types & How to Dress Them

Body type: Straight

This is the most common body type. Over 45% of American women have a Straight body shape (sometimes called rectangle or ruler). This means that the hips and bust are balanced and the waist is not very defined. Straight body types probably have a bottom that is more flat than round. They tend to gain weight in the torso first and then in the upper thighs and arms. Their lower legs are always shapely and one of the best assets.

How to Dress a Straight Body Shape

The key to dressing a Straight body type is to proportionally dress the top and bottom of the body while enhancing the waist. They can wear form fitting clothing (such as a tube-type dress) and create a waist by adding a wide, dark belt. However, to create a more curvaceous effect, add volume (or the illusion of volume) proportionally to the upper and lower body by mixing and matching separates.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - Pair color of similar or identical brightness on the upper and lower body, while adding darker color around your waist.
• Pair a light colored dress with a wide dark belt.
• Pair a shirt that is lighted colored around the bust/shoulders and dark below the bust with light colored pants or a skirt.

Body type is: Pear

A Pear Body type (sometimes called triangle), is when the hips are larger than the bust and there is a nicely defined waist. Pears have an elegant neck and proportionately slim arms and shoulders. They first gain weight in the bottom and legs followed by the tummy and upper body. The waist is the best asset so don''t be afraid to show it off.

How to Dress a Pear Body Shape

The key to dressing a pear body type is to enhance and add volume (or the illusion of volume) to the upper body while emphasizing the waist and de-emphasizing the lower body to create a balanced, hourglass appearance. Strapless dresses and tops look good on a Pear Body, but you can create a more curvaceous effect and add volume to the upper half by mixing and matching separates.

Tip: Create Balance with Color – Pair light colors on the upper body with dark colors on the lower body.
• Suggest dark wash jeans and stay away from whiskering (faded vertical lines) at the hips.

Body type: Spoon

A Spoon Body type (sometimes called figure 8), is when hips are larger than the bust and there is a defined waist. The hips have a "shelf" appearance, and spoon body types are prone to gaining weight in the tummy and have a tendency towards love-handles. Spoon body types may gain weight in the upper thighs and upper arms, but the lower legs and arms are shapely and the best assets.

How to Dress a Spoon Body Shape

The key to dressing a Spoon body type is to draw attention to the upper body while deemphasizing the tummy and hips to create a more balanced appearance and create the illusion of an hourglass figure. Strapless dresses and tops look great, and since the legs are one of the best assets, feel free to play with skirt lengths and show them off.

Tip: Create balance with color – Look for clothing that is lighter around the bust and shoulders.
• The problem area is most likely the tummy. Shirts and dresses that are darker in mid-section and lighter on top will create the most flattering effect.

Body type: Hourglass

The Hourglass body type is the one that most women strive for. The bust and hips are well balanced and there is a beautifully defined waist. Hourglass shapes have gently rounded shoulders that align nicely with the hips. The waist is obvious and gracefully curves out to the hips. They most likely have a rounded bottom and beautiful side as well as front profile. The upper body is proportionate in length to the legs which are shapely. From top to bottom, the Hourglass is a picture of harmony and balance.

How to Dress an Hourglass Body Shape

The key to dressing an Hourglass body type is to proportionally dress the top and bottom of the body while accentuating the waist. Wide belts over shirts and dresses are a great way to show off the waist. Create an even more curvaceous effect by proportionally adding a bit of volume to the upper and lower body, but always try to maintain balance since it is the best asset. Feel free to play with skirt lengths to show off great legs.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - Pair colors of similar or identical brightness on the upper and lower body, while adding darker color around the waist to accentuate curves.
• Pair a light colored dress with a wide dark belt.
• Pair a shirt that is lighted colored around the bust/shoulders and dark below the bust, and put it with light colored pants or a skirt.

Body type: Top Hourglass

Top Hourglass Body Types have a beautifully defined waist and bust that is larger than the hips. They have gently rounded shoulders that align nicely with the hips. The waist is obvious and gracefully curves out to the hips. They most likely have a rounded bottom and beautiful side as well as front profile. Their upper body is proportionate in length to their legs which are shapely.

How to Dress a Top Hourglass Body Shape

The key to dressing a Top Hourglass body type is to balance the lower body with the ample bust while accentuating the enviable waist. This is achieved by selecting clothing cuts that will fill out the lower half. Feel free to play with skirt lengths and show off shapely legs.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - Look for dresses and separates that are dark around the bust and monochromatic below the bust to create the illusion of a balanced figure.
• Pair a light or bright colored strapless dress with a dark band around the bust.
• Pair a shirt that is dark colored around the bust/shoulders and light in color below the bust with light colored pants or a skirt.

Body type: Inverted Triangle

Inverted Triangle body types have a proportionally larger upper body with broad shoulders, and ample bust and a wide back. The hips are slim and the bottom may be on the flat side. The waist is subtle and Inverted Triangles have a tendency to gain weight in the belly and upper body. Beautiful, shapely legs are the best asset.

How to Dress an Inverted Triangle Body Shape

The key to dressing an Inverted Triangle body type is to balance the broader shoulders, chest and back with the narrower lower body to create more of an hourglass effect. This is achieved by choosing clothes that add curves to the hips and bottom while creating a more defined waist. Feel free to show off amazing legs so play with skirt lengths, but don''t go too short otherwise this will further a topheavy look.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - Look for dresses and separates that are dark above the waist and light or bright below to create the illusion of a balanced figure.
• Pick a dress has a dark colored bodice and light skirt.
• Pair a shirt that is dark colored around the bust/shoulders and brighter in color below the bust with light colored pants or a skirt.

Body type: Oval

Oval body types have a large bust, narrow hips, and a full midsection. They have a tendency to gain weight in the stomach, back and upper body. The waist is undefined and the widest part of their frame. They also have a full, shorter neck and full face. The buttocks are somewhat flat and the legs are slender. Shapely legs are their best asset.

How to Dress an Oval Body Shape

The key to dressing an Oval body type is to de-emphasize the midsection and create a more defined waist. This is achieved by choosing clothing that adds curves and fullness to the lower body and tops that taper to a waist. Stay away from tight clothing (such as a tube-type dress). Feel free to show off amazing legs so play with skirt lengths, but don''t go too short otherwise this will further a top-heavy look.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - A monochromatic look usually works best. Add splashed of color with camisoles, earrings, necklaces and great shoes.
• Wear a dark colored dress with a wide dark belt.
• Wear a dark pant or skirt suit with a bright colored cami and shoes.

Body type: Diamond

Diamond body types have hips that are broader than the bust and shoulders and a full midsection. They have a tendency to gain weight in their stomach, back, hips and buttocks. The waist is undefined and the widest part of the frame. They carry some weight in the upper legs, but the lower legs are shapely and one of their most attractive features. They also have proportionately slender, shapely arms.

How to Dress a Diamond Body Shape

The key to dressing a Diamond body type is to balance the shoulders and bust with the hips while creating a waist. This is achieved by choosing clothing that adds curves and fullness to the upper body with appropriate clothing cuts while choosing pants and skirts that will lean and lengthen the lower body. They have amazing lower legs and beautiful arms, so feel free to show them off. Stay away from tight clothing (such as a tube-type dress). To create the most curvaceous effect, mix and match separates and play up their face.

Tip: Create Curves with Color - A monochromatic look usually works best. Add splashed of color with wraps, earrings, and necklaces.
• Wear a dark colored dress with a wide dark belt.
• Wear a dark pant or skirt suit with a bright colored cami/scarf.', 'This comprehensive style guide covers eight female body types (Straight, Pear, Spoon, Hourglass, Top Hourglass, Inverted Triangle, Oval, Diamond) with detailed descriptions of each body shape''s characteristics and specific styling recommendations. Each section provides key dressing strategies focused on creating balance and enhancing the best features, along with color coordination tips and specific clothing suggestions.', 'style_guide', '{"Body Type Styling","Customer Service","Product Knowledge"}', 'ready', NULL, '2026-04-14 17:56:17.53068', '2026-04-14 17:56:39.301'),
	('a2b9b5c0-aeaa-4998-860e-8bc4547ee90d', 'b0396051-34a1-475b-addc-771e580a5224', '46870047', 'LS Operations Manual.pdf', 'pdf', 'Libby Story 
Employee Operations 
Manual 
 
"Where Fashion is Art." 
100 – WELCOME TO LIBBY STORY
The McRight Family and the entire management team are excited to have you as part of our operations. We are extremely proud of 
all of our stores and are anxious to show Ridgeland and the surrounding community the best experience in fashion and customer
service available. We will strive at all time to surpass the expectations of our customers, and the requirements of our clients. Please 
remember that the more successful we become as a whole, the more successful you become as an individual.
At Libby Story, we are fashion lovers, vintage seekers, craft makers, hard workers, and most of all—individuals. Libby Story is all 
about the unique, creative spirit in each of us. Our mission at Libby Story is to provide apparel, accessories, décor and service in 
such a way that each customer feels their purchases were tailor made for them. We provide small batch-runs, one-of-a-kind and 
vintage items to ensure our customers can build and express their creativity and individuality with our products. We also emphasize 
creativity in our stores and on our website through art, DIYs, crafts, and unique displays to provide an inspiring environment for our 
guests to enjoy. Our mission is recognized from the moment a customer enters our stores. Our customer''s experience is one of 
inspiration, excitement, fun, happiness, professionalism and warmth. It is our goal that each of our customers leaves feeling 
inspired, loved, needed, and appreciated. We are determined to attain this level of service, and we can only reach such a goal with 
100% of our employees working in harmony together. 
101 History
Libby Story was established in 2004 by Libby and her husband, John Hunter McRight. Libby Story, Libby''s maiden name, has 
become synonymous with creativity and style. It all started in Greenville, MS (the heart of the Mississippi Delta) when Libby was 
only 16 years old. She began working at a women''s retail store called "Gail''s." She soon realized that she was destined to work in 
the fashion industry. She continued to work at Gail''s all through high school and during her college breaks from MSU. Libby began 
going to markets and buying for Gail''s when she was 19. When she graduated from college, she was already managing Gail''s and 
had begun designing and wholesaling her own jewelry line to stores throughout Mississippi. However, she was uncertain as to 
whether she would take one of several department store jobs offered to her in larger cities. Not wanting to sacrifice her creativity, 
she decided to open her own store. 
The first Libby Story opened in Greenville, MS. This is where Libby was raised, and after working for Gail''s, this is where she saw 
the need for a creative and fashion-forward company. Libby''s deep connection with her Grandmother and her Grandmother''s closet 
played a large role in Libby''s need to merge past and present, to preserve the past, while forging into the future. Libby''s charming 
craftiness, wit, large assortment of unique clothing and accessories, plus her killer handmade jewelry line made the store an instant 
success. This success made the launch of additional stores across the state a no-brainer. Starkville, MS was the second place the 
McRights decided to expand their talent to, and then came Ridgeland. After the success of the first Ridgeland location, the 
McRights decided to expand again and move the flagship Libby Story to a much larger location at the Renaissance. Still constantly 
and unceasingly crafting, creating, designing, and dreaming, Libby is truly the essence of the Libby Story girl.
Libby Story is owned by the McRight family. John Hunter and Libby are the founders and play an active role in the creative 
department and overall supervision of Libby Story. 
102 The Libby Story Girl
The Libby Story girl is unique and independent. She is creative, hard-working, and has a large imagination. She likes to make 
things and has no qualms with getting her hands dirty and trying something new. She loves the hunt of finding new, trendy items, 
as well as items that others might discard or overlook. It is a combination of the two elements that creates her truly unique look.

200 – EMPLOYMENT
Libby Story is only as good as the people that work with us. We acknowledge that our workers are a vital part of our company and 
a vital part of our customer''s experience. Since our humble beginnings, we have built a reputation of being a unique and friendly 
place to shop, and to continue that reputation, we aim to hire the best and brightest workers. Yes, our expectations are high, but
the experience and opportunities are bright. 
201 Employee Selection
Libby Story selects its employees through advertising, referrals, word-of-mouth, written application, and by personal interviews and 
careful reference checking. We interview several candidates prior to selecting those who demonstrate the ability, experience, skills 
and cooperative spirit that we seek in our employees. Congratulations on making it through the whole process and becoming an 
employee with our company. We are honored to have you join our team. 
202 Sexual Harassment
While all forms of harassment are prohibited, Libby Story has an explicit policy prohibiting the sexual harassment of its employees. 
Specifically, sexual harassment means unwelcome sexual advances, requests for sexual favors, and/or other verbal or physical 
conduct of a sexual nature. 
Management has the responsibility to maintain a workplace free of any form of sexual harassment. That means that Management 
shall not threaten or insinuate, either explicitly or implicitly, that an employee''s refusal to submit to sexual advances will adversely 
affect the employee''s employment, evaluation, wages, advancement, assigned duties, shifts, or any other condition of employment 
or career development. 
If you believe that the actions or words of a customer, delivery person, Manager or fellow employee constitute unwelcome sexual 
harassment, you have a responsibility to report that behavior to your Manager immediately. All complaints of harassment will be 
investigated discreetly and promptly. Any employee, supervisor, or manager who, after investigation, is found to have engaged in 
harassment will be subject to appropriate disciplinary action, up to and including termination.
Any employee who makes management aware of sexual harassment activities will not suffer adverse job consequences as a result 
of a complaint.
203 Performance Reviews
Performance reviews are administered for new employees during the Orientation Period, and quarterly, or as required, thereafter. 
Increases in pay are not automatic and are based on merit and productivity.
204 Separation from Employment
Employees who voluntarily resign are required to give a 14-day notice for the training and orientation of a new employee. This 
assists Libby Story in finding a suitable replacement for you and in maintaining a high level of customer service. 
Any employee can be terminated for misconduct, poor performance, or failure to comply with company policies. 
Final paychecks are issued on the next scheduled payday, and your final paystub will be mailed to you.
205 Orientation Period
All new employees of Libby Story participate in a 30 day Orientation Period conducted by their Supervisor used to familiarize the 
employees both with Libby Story and with each other.
The Orientation Period may be extended if necessary.
All employees are reviewed at the end of this time to discuss areas of strength, those needing improvement, and are encouraged to 
ask any questions. If the employee is unsuited for the assigned job, it is understood they could be reassigned, or terminated, from 
employment at any time during, or after, the Orientation Period.
206 Full-Time Employees
Full-time hourly non-exempt (non-salaried employees) are classified as employees that regularly work a minimum of 35 hours per 
week and are paid on an hourly basis. Regularly is defined by the average of the prior 26 weeks. 
Full-time hourly non-exempt managers (non-salaried employees) are classified as employees that regularly work a minimum of 38 
hours per week and are paid on an hourly plus commission basis. Regularly is defined by the average of the prior 26 weeks.

Full-time exempt employees (salaried employees) regularly work a minimum of 40 hours per week and are paid on a salaried 
basis. Regularly is defined by the average of the prior 26 weeks.
All full-time employees (salaried and hourly employees) are entitled to all benefits outlined in this Handbook.
207 Part-time Employees
Part-time hourly non-exempt employees are those regularly working less than 35 hours, per week. Regularly is defined by the 
average of the prior 26 weeks.
Part-time employees are eligible for statutory benefits as outlined in this Handbook. Part time employees are not eligible for paid 
vacation.

300 – SCHEDULING
301 Hours of Operation
Libby Story hours of operation vary from location to location. 
The normal workweek for the Libby Story Ridgeland location is seven days a week, or as dictated by the Renaissance 
management/customer needs. The hours you work may be changed to adjust for management or customer needs. Libby Story 
Ridgeland normal hours of operations are:
Monday – Thursday: 10 AM to 7 PM
Friday – Saturday: 10 AM to 8 PM
Sunday: 1 PM to 6 PM
Holiday Hours (Christmas season) Monday - Saturday: 9 AM to 9 PM
The only hours the Renaissance observes are Easter, Thanksgiving Day and Christmas Day. Expect to be open normal 
store hours on any given holiday other than those we are closed. 
The normal workweek for the Libby Story Starkville location is six days a week, or as dictated by the owners/management. The
hours you work may be changed to adjust for management or customer needs. Libby Story Starkville normal hours of operations 
are:
Monday – Friday: 10 AM to 6 PM
Saturday: 10 AM to 5 PM
Home Game Saturday: 9 AM to 6 PM
Sunday: Closed except on home football game weekends.
Home Game Sunday: 11 AM to 3 PM
The only hours the Starkville store observes are Fourth of July, Easter, Thanksgiving Day, and Christmas Day. Expect to 
be open normal store hours on any given holiday other than those we are closed. 
Libby Story employees are expected to report for their work shifts one hour prior to opening and to stay until the last customer 
leaves and chores are completed. Our hours of operations do change during the Christmas holiday shopping season and 
for certain holidays and special occasions throughout the year. Expect to be scheduled for any other times around those 
holidays and occasions. 
302 Schedules
All schedules are posted through Google docs online. Each employee must have a gmail account to check your schedule. Be sure 
to check the schedule every time you work to make sure there are no changes or added staff meetings. Once a schedule is posted, 
there is no asking for time off. You may swap shifts with another employee with management approval. If you have any questions 
or concerns, feel free to discuss them with management in person or via email. 
Requests for regular time off are handled via email only. Check the Requests Off tab on your schedule for "Black Out" dates before 
making a request for time off. "Black Out" dates are days that no one is allowed off due to store needs, or days that might have 
been requested off by other employees first. Requests for Paid Time Off are handled via the Libby Story Request Off Form only. 
This form tracks vacation time used and vacation time available. 
Requests for time off are granted on a first come, first serve basis. Please note, a request for time off is simply that…a request, not 
a guarantee. 
303 Meal / Break Periods
All employees who work a shift of more than six hours, receive, and are encouraged to use, their one half (1/2) hour 
unpaid meal period each day as a break from their daily responsibilities. 
All employees on the retail sales floor are not allowed to take meal periods/breaks during the critical customer periods. Meal 
periods will be scheduled and approved by management each work shift.
304 Overtime
Depending on Libby Story workload, employees may be required to work overtime. Overtime is paid to hourly employees at one and 
one-half times the regular hourly rate for over forty (40) hours worked in a week.
Management will make every effort to give employees as much notice as possible of necessary overtime. All overtime must be 
approved by Management prior to its being worked. There will be no unauthorized overtime.
Only hours actually worked will be counted for overtime. Any other paid time such as vacation, holiday time, or bonus time will not 
count toward overtime calculations.

305 Clocking In / Out
In accordance with Government regulations, all companies are required to record time worked on a daily basis, to compute pay and 
keep a record of attendance. Lunch periods and breaks must be recorded, along with any time an employee is absent during the
day.
 The following procedures must be adhered to at all times.
All work performed must be while clocked in.
Work only those hours posted, following your name on the work schedule. You will be paid only for your scheduled and 
approved time.
Your supervisor must approve any change from the work schedule, including overtime assignments.
You must clock in when ready to work at the beginning of each work shift and immediately at the end of each work shift.
If, for some reason, you forget to clock in / out, report to a manger or the office. 
Falsifying or altering a time record; failing to check in or out; or recording or falsifying a time record for another employee is 
strictly prohibited by law, and can lead to disciplinary action up to and including dismissal for both employees.
All employees will be paid at the correct rate of pay. If you have any problem with your pay, contact your Manager 
immediately.
All breaks must be communicated and approved by a manager or supervisor.
306 Staff Meetings
To improve our skills, or learn about new procedures, products, or services, employees will be required to attend all mandatory staff 
meetings. Staff meetings are typically conducted once per month, and advance notice will be given in most cases. Not attending 
required staff meetings will result in disciplinary action, up to or including dismissal. Employees will be paid their typical rate of pay 
for required meetings. 
307 Inclement Weather
School and government closings during inclement weather do not equal to Libby Story store closings. In general, if there is 
inclement weather all employees are to report and/or remain at work unless a manager notifies you differently. 
Snow and/or Ice Conditions: 
If there is snow and/or ice on the roads, all employees should report for work, unless the manager on duty notifies you personally 
and tells you differently. 
Severe Thunderstorm and/or Tornado Watch:
All Libby Story locations remain open during severe thunderstorms and tornado watches. All employees should report for work and 
continue to work as usual. You will be notified if there are any changes. 
Tornado Warning:
During the event of a tornado warning, all Libby Story locations are to follow this procedure:
Notify all customers and employees in the store of the warning.
Allow customers a 10 minute window to leave store premises.
Lock the store''s front and back doors for the remainder of the actual tornado warning.
Take cover in a central location free from falling objects and glass. Libby Story Ridgeland employees and/or customers 
should take cover in the central dressing room area. Libby Story Starkville employees and/or customers should take cover 
in the dressing room hallway. 
After the tornado warning is over, unlock all doors and resume business as usual. 
NOTE: You will be notified differently if you are to do anything beyond the procedure as outlined above. Do not call the store 
owners, Headquarters, Renaissance management offices, surrounding stores, or any other managers asking for instructions or if it 
is okay to close down. During the event of catastrophic damage or injuries, contact 911 for emergency help.

400 – ATTENDANCE
Employees are expected to report to work on time each day to begin work at the assigned time. Each person is very important to 
the smooth operation of Libby Story. Absence and tardiness can create a hardship for other employees and our customers.
If you will be absent you must personally, notify your manager three hours before your scheduled starting time so 
arrangements can be made for someone else to handle your duties. It is also your responsibility to assist in replacing yourself on 
the schedule.
Asking a relative, friend or another person to call in for you is not acceptable! Texting or emailing your call in is not 
acceptable!
Any employee who does not report for work and fails to call in for ANY work shift will have voluntarily resigned from their position.
401 Tardiness
Because of the unfair burden placed on Libby Story''s customers and other employees, chronic tardiness is not acceptable and may 
be cause for disciplinary action, up to and including dismissal. If you are going to be late, you must notify your Manager by phone, 
not by text message. Call the manager''s personal cell phone if you open in the morning, but you know you will be late. Being 
tardy more than four times in a 6 month period will result in termination. After one (1) tardy, you will receive a verbal 
warning. After two (2) tardies,', 'Libby Story 
