	('ecfa1b75-9b5a-4154-9cbf-1ff6bab9ea74', 'b0396051-34a1-475b-addc-771e580a5224', 'ai_item', '4f780d47-6439-4f31-9e12-8d7c07e92f3f', 'Customer Retention Statistics and Cost Impact | Key statistics showing the financial impact of customer retention versus acquisition, demonstrating why keeping existing customers is more profitable than finding new ones. | Cost of Customer Acquisition vs Retention | It costs 5-6 times more to acquire a new customer than to retain an existing one. For medium-sized companies, just a 1% reduction in customer service problems could generate an extra $16 million in profits over 5 years. Customer loyalty is worth up to 10 times the value of a single purchase. | Why Customers Leave | 68% of customer defection occurs because customers feel poorly treated by staff - this is the leading cause of customer loss. Only 14% leave due to product dissatisfaction, 9% for competitive reasons, 3% move away, and 1% die. Reducing customer defections can boost profits by 25-85%. | Silent Dissatisfaction | Only 4% of dissatisfied customers actually complain - 96% simply leave without saying anything. For every customer who complains, 26 others remain silent. Of those who don''t complain, 91% will never return to do business again.', 'a7793fce9a9ccc19', '[-0.015373173,-0.011283504,0.04563034,0.0023780887,0.011433544,0.02200395,0.07247013,0.04754434,0.06563334,-0.05982907,0.097555354,0.059963066,0.05897178,-0.040850192,0.08324459,-0.016704604,0.033449423,-0.015720613,-0.10864589,0.00553258,-0.10756124,-0.06748245,-0.07132802,0.06292247,0.031559445,-0.084450155,0.02259601,0.0024784363,-0.0060219634,-0.07232122,-0.026005799,0.09808418,0.07324004,-0.039931778,0.017483935,-0.003379287,-0.038092263,-0.012249777,-0.034580886,-0.03637652,0.017384855,-0.030949412,-0.080919474,0.030108083,0.02222499,-0.037510682,0.019074418,0.05424819,0.020164778,0.09733967,-0.0047340975,-0.014506806,0.011155417,0.0031737518,0.0057246475,-0.007975142,0.05321533,-0.04833961,-0.107281595