	('0afabed1-9bc0-4436-97cb-74f9dbad030a', 'b0396051-34a1-475b-addc-771e580a5224', 'knowledge_doc', '43363e98-6ab7-47ad-b1b6-b4b147ccd668:chunk:0', '[Sales Training - Greeting & Building Rapport.docx] Sales Training:  Greeting & Building Rapport

"You never get a second chance to make a first impression."  This statement is true, especially in retail.  

Enticing customers to come in the door is hard enough, so what if they are turned off by how they are greeted, or worse yet, by being ignored?  It only takes a few seconds to make an impression, so don''t let it be a bad one.

Every day we have customers entering the store, and studies show that customers form an impression (good or bad) of the store in as little as 20 seconds.  Therefore, in Libby Story stores, we focus on the "Stop and Drop in 15" Rule.  Think of it like your childhood fire drill, "Stop, Drop, and Roll," but it''s "Stop and Drop in 15!"

This simple rule defines how you should act in those first few crucial seconds.  Let''s look:

