	('f57a4ce3-e44c-4da3-9af8-067d6842323e', 'b0396051-34a1-475b-addc-771e580a5224', 'knowledge_doc', '019d0c42-e8e3-4486-b69d-a9398fee79b2:chunk:3', '[Tips for Improving Language on the Sales Floor.docx] right for you.  This is what I can do…" 

"I''m New Here"

Being a new employee is not an excuse for being unable to effectively assist a customer.  Your customer wants to make a purchase, have their questions answered, or have their problem solved.  Customers are pretty patient for the most part and will work with a new retail associate who is polite and works hard to help them.  

Better Alternative:  "Please bear with me and I''ll get you the help you need."

"Hold On"

This customer service phrase should be non-existent.  There is a much softer way to say essentially the same thing without infuriating the customer.  

Better Alternative:  "Are you able to hold for a moment?" or "It''s going to be few moments, do you mind waiting?"

"I''m Busy Right Now"

Without customers, we wouldn''t have a job.  You are never too busy to help a customer.  

Better Alternative:  "I''d be happy to help you."

"You''re Wrong"

