	('c3108e17-1805-4aa1-9d10-37c3426b86f9', 'b0396051-34a1-475b-addc-771e580a5224', 'knowledge_doc', '43ab573c-ea3b-4aed-8499-7b1e2e0e7750:chunk:8', '[Sales Training Manual.docx] hat they have tried on thus far, find a few more items and nonchalantly place them on their door and let them know you have found a few more options for them. 

NOTE: Giving a customer too many options can confuse them and lead to no sale at all. It’s always helpful to offer to clear out any unwanted items for the customer as they are trying on to avoid clutter and confusion. 



Step Three: Once you feel confident that they have found what they are looking for it’s a great idea to suggest items that complement what they have found or complete their look. 

NOTE: If the customer is just browsing and not looking for anything specific, pay attention to what they are adding so that you can suggest matching items once they are trying on.   

When giving your opinion of the outfit and how it looks be HONEST and suggestive! You don’t want them to buy it and then get home and their best friend tells them that it looks terrible on them.  



